Definition 5.7. Let $(s,t)$ be a normalized modular data of a modular category ${\mathcal{C}}$, and $n=\operatorname{ord}(t)$. The image of the elementary 2-subgroup ${\Omega^{n}_{2}}$ of $\operatorname{Gal}(\mathbb{Q}_{n}/\mathbb{Q})$ under the restriction map $\operatorname{res}^{\mathbb{Q}_{n}}_{\mathbb{Q}(S)}:\operatorname{Gal}(\mathbb% {Q}_{n}/\mathbb{Q})\to G_{\mathcal{C}}$ is called the characteristic 2-group of ${\mathcal{C}}$, and denoted by $H_{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 7.1. We call a super-modular category ${\mathcal{C}}$ transitive if the $\operatorname{Gal}(\bar{\mathbb{Q}})$-action on $\overline{\operatorname{Irr}({\mathcal{C}})}$ is transitive.
Definition 7.12. Let $\mathcal{E}$ be a symmetric fusion category, and ${\mathcal{C}}$ a nondegenerate braided fusion category ${\mathcal{C}}$ over $\mathcal{E}$. We say that ${\mathcal{C}}$ is $\mathcal{E}$-prime if it has no nondegenerate braided fusion subcategory over $\mathcal{E}$ except $\mathcal{E}$ and ${\mathcal{C}}$. An $\mathcal{E}$-prime braided fusion category is called $\mathcal{E}$-simple if it is not pointed. For $\mathcal{E}={\operatorname{sVec}}$, we simply use the terms s-prime and s-simple instead of ${\operatorname{sVec}}$-prime and ${\operatorname{sVec}}$-simple.
Definition 3.1. A modular category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is said to be transitive if $G_{\mathcal{C}}$ (or $\operatorname{Gal}(\bar{\mathbb{Q}})$) acts transitively on $\operatorname{Irr}({\mathcal{C}})$, i.e., $|\operatorname{Orb}({\mathcal{C}})|=1$.
Definition 5.2. A level $m$ representation $(\phi,W)$ of $\operatorname{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$ is called minimal if $\dim(W)=\varphi_{2}(m)$ and ${\operatorname{spec}(\phi(\mathfrak{t}))}=\{\sigma^{2}(\zeta_{m}^{l})\mid% \sigma\in\operatorname{Gal}(\mathbb{Q}_{m}/\mathbb{Q})\}$ for some $l\in{(\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z})^{\times}}$. In this case, $(\phi,W)$ or the corresponding $\operatorname{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{Z})$-module is said to be minimal of type $l$.
Definition 7 (state complexity). Let $\Xi\subseteq W_{O_{K}}^{a}(O_{\bar{K}})$ be any finite set of integral Witt vectors. We say that a DFA $\mathfrak{A}$ generates $\Xi$ if for every $\xi\in\Xi$ there exists an output function $\tau:S_{\mathfrak{A}}\rightarrow O_{\bar{K}}$ such that $\mathfrak{A}_{\tau}$ generates $\xi$. The state complexity of $\Xi$, denoted by $c_{\Xi}$, is then defined as the minimum size $\min\#S_{\mathfrak{A}}$ of the state set $S_{\mathfrak{A}}$ of those DFA $\mathfrak{A}$ which can generate $\Xi$.
Definition 4 ($2$-dimensional $\mathbb{Q}$-lattice). A ($2$-dimensional) $\mathbb{Q}$-lattice is a pair $(\Lambda,\phi)$ of a lattice $\Lambda$ in $\mathbb{C}$ and a homomorphism $\phi:\mathbb{Q}^{2}/\mathbb{Z}^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{Q}\Lambda/\Lambda$.
Definition 3 ($K$-lattices; [Connes_Marcolli_Ramachandran]). A ($1$-dimensional) $K$-lattice is a pair $(\Lambda,\phi)$ of a finitely generated $O_{K}$-submodule $\Lambda$ of $\mathbb{C}$ such that $K\otimes_{O_{K}}\Lambda\simeq K$ and a homomorphism $\phi:K/O_{K}\rightarrow K\Lambda/\Lambda$.
Definition 2 (the Deligne-Ribet monoid $DR_{K}$). The Deligne-Ribet monoid $DR_{K}$ is the profinite monoid defined as the following inverse limit of the above inverse system of the ray class monoids $DR_{\mathfrak{f}}$: $\displaystyle DR_{K}$ $\displaystyle:=$ $\displaystyle\lim_{\mathfrak{f}\in I_{K}}DR_{\mathfrak{f}}.$
Definition 1 (the category $\mathscr{C}_{K}$). The objects of the category $\mathscr{C}_{K}$ [Borger_Smit11] are the $\Lambda$-rings that are finite etale over $K$ and have integral models (cf. Remark 4, pp.544 [Uramoto18]); the arrows of $\mathscr{C}_{K}$ are the $\Lambda$-ring homomorphisms over $K$ between them.
Definition 6 ($\mathcal{J}$-equivalence). Let $M$ be a commutative monoid. For two elements $s,s^{\prime}\in M$, we denote as $s\leq_{\mathcal{J}}s^{\prime}$ if we have an inclusion of the (both-sided) ideals $sM\subseteq s^{\prime}M$, or in other words, there exists $m\in M$ such that $s=s^{\prime}m$. Furthermore, we denote as $s\sim_{\mathcal{J}}s^{\prime}$ and say that $s$ and $s^{\prime}$ are $\mathcal{J}$-equivalent if $s\leq_{\mathcal{J}}s^{\prime}$ and $s^{\prime}\leq_{\mathcal{J}}s$. The set of $\mathcal{J}$-equivalent classes is denoted as $M/\mathcal{J}$.
