Definition 5 ($\Lambda$-ring $X_{\Xi}$). Let $\Xi\subseteq W_{O_{K}}^{a}(O_{\bar{K}})$ be a finite subset. Then the associated $\Lambda$-ring $X_{\Xi}$ is defined as follows: $\displaystyle X_{\Xi}$ $\displaystyle:=$ $\displaystyle K\otimes O_{K}[I_{K}\Xi],$ where $I_{K}\Xi$ is the orbit of $\Xi$ under the action of $\psi_{\mathfrak{a}}$s ($\mathfrak{a}\in I_{K}$).
Definition 4.6. We denote by ${\bf Q}_{m}$ the quiver with one vertex and $m$ loops.
Definition 4.3. We will say that a thick subcategory $\mathcal{T}\subset D^{b}(\operatorname{coh}C)$ is proper if $\mathcal{T}\neq 0,D^{b}(\operatorname{coh}C)$. We call $\mathcal{T}$ torsion (resp. torsion-free) in case (1) (resp. (2)) in Corollary 4.2 holds.
Definition 3.3. A triangulated category $\mathcal{T}$ is called quiver-like if there exists a finite quiver $Q$ and an equivalence of triangulated categories $D^{b}_{0}(Q)\simeq\mathcal{T}$.
Definition 3.7. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with an enhancement. A collection of objects $\{t_{1},\ldots,t_{n}\}$ is $\mathcal{T}$ is called vertex-like if the endomorphism dg algebra ${\mathbb{R}}\operatorname{End}(\oplus t_{i})$ is formal, and in addition $\operatorname{Hom}(t_{i},t_{j})=\delta_{ij}\cdot\mathsf{k}$, and $\operatorname{Hom}^{p}(t_{i},t_{j})=0$ for all $i,j$ and $p\neq 0,1$.
Definition 4.5. A quiver $Q$ is called realizable if the category $D^{b}_{0}(Q)$ is equivalent to a thick finitely generated subcategory of $D^{b}(\operatorname{coh}C)$ for a smooth projective curve over an algebraically closed field $\mathsf{k}$.
Definition 2.5. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category equipped with a faithful functor $U\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathbf{Pos}$. A pair of morphisms $C\xrightarrow{f}D\xrightarrow{g}C$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is an embedding-retraction-pair (e-r-p) provided $(U(f),U(g))$ is an adjoint pair, and $U(f)$ is injective.8It follows from these two conditions that $U(f)$ is an embedding with left inverse $U(g)$. Further, such an e-r-p is said to be finite if $U(C)$ is finite.
Definition 2.7. Let $X$ be a spectral space, and $L$ its dual lattice. We say that $X$ and $L$ are bifinite provided the following two equivalent conditions are satisfied: 1. $X$ is the cofiltered limit of the retractions of its finite e-r-p’s; 2. $L$ is the filtered colimit of the embeddings of its finite e-r-p’s.
